=== division between logic and metaphysics ===
It is well known that Kant's opinions about the prospect of further developments
in logic was completely wrong
    (Bviii) It is remarkable also that to the present day this logic has not
    been able to advance a single step, and is thus to all appearance a closed
    and completed body of doctrine.
The developments of Frege to bring logic
up to the level of complexity required to capture recursively enumerable sets of
sentences as theorems is still 100 years off.

But more importantly Kant offers to explain this completeness as due to logic
being <q>quite precisely delimited; its sole concern is to give an exhaustive
exposition and a strict proof of the formal rules of all thought, whether it be
_a priori_ or empirical</q>.

One wonders what Kant means by <q>formal</q>, surely not the modern view of
rules specified purely in terms of the shapes and sequences of symbols without
reliance unpon their meanings. <q>Strict proof</q> is also somewhat unclear, or
at least foreign to modern logic - how might one _prove_ an axiom of logic,
or offer it any greater cfeedence than it already has? (inference to best
explanation, or because of the fruitfulness of its consequences is urely not
what Kant has in mind.)

metaphysical claims one must suppose, are by contrast those in which the
validity of the reasoning, or the necessity of the claim, depends upon the content
content (i.e. the actual predicate occupying a place) and not merely the form. 
i.e.  logical laws are those that remain valid when a concept is consistently
replaced with another, wheras such substitution can change a metaphysical
necessity into a falsehood.

If this interpretation is correct then logical truths are neither analytic nor
synthetic (unless the notion of containment is stretched enough to include
containment of logical structure, but that seems implausible).

=== causal necessity not distinguished from absolute ===
    (Bxiii) Accidental observations, made in obedience to no previously
    thought-out plan, can never be made to yield a necessary law, which alone
    reason is concerned to discover.

Here we have the ancient refusal to distinguish between causal(/nomological)
necessity and conceptual(/analytic/logical) necessity.
=== hint of argument against idealism ===
Kant repeatedly displays his awareness of the threat of self-contradiction in
asserting that we positively know of the existence of objects about which we can
know nothing.

Why posit noumena? We need a positive reasom. In the introduction the closest we
come is
    (Bxxvi) But our further contention must be duly borne in mind namely that
    though we cannot _know_ these objects as things themselves we must yet be in
    position at least _think_ them as things in themselves; otherwise we should
    be landed in the absurd conclusion they can be appearance without anything
    that appears.

This first hint, at least, is not particularly promising. It seems to hinge
a definitional stop. If these things we experience are not
appearances (and hence have some external/noumenal obejects that they are
appearances of) then let us call them something else. The question then simply
becomes what reason do we have for thinking that our ewxperienfes are
appearances, and to this, as yet, Kant has ventured no answer

== introduction ==
=== a priori ===
Nowhere here is Kant explicit about _a priori_ knowledge being *justified*
without experience. Instead we find talk of <q>independent of experience</q> or
_a posteriori_ knowledge as <q>has its sources _a posteriori_</q> or <q>arises
out of experience</q>. The distinction between the origins, sources or
<q>arising out of</q> is left unclear. If we accept, for the moment, the
justified true belief analysis, one might have knowledge that a subject would
not _believe_ without experience or that would not be justified without
experience. It is the kind of tiring prolixity that makes reading Kant such a
slog.

This potential confusion is exacerbated by Kant's claim that <q>Every
alteration has its cause</q> is _a priori_ but not purely _a priori_ on the
grounds that <q>alteration is a concept which can be derived only from
experience</q>. This <q>derivation</q> suggests that we cannot form the concept
and hence, presumably, not form the judgement <q>Every alteration has its
cause</q> without experience, regardless of whether or not we would have any
justification for believing or disbelieving it. This distinction between _a
priori_ and _a posteriori_ *concepts* is thus far very dubious and we have no
guide apart from this sole example on how to draw it.

Still the very fact that this is distinguished as an impure _a priori_
proposition, goes further to suggest that it is justification that is in
question. It appears that Kant/the translators can be only criticised for lack
of clarity on this point and that on reflection it must be that _a priori_
truths are those of which knowledge can be justified without experience. This is
taken for granted, or as a definitional stipulation, in most modern ENglish
speaking introductions to philosophy and it is merely of interest that it is put
so unclearly in its most influential early exposition.

==== criterion ====
Necessity and certain universality as criterion of _a priority_.

Though counterexamples to these criteria have been constructed with the use of
indexicals, they remain as the touchstone of my own enquiries, even though I
ultimately give up on all three. Certainly, our knowledge of necessity could
never be justified by experience. Is the underlying justification that there is
no necessary connection between distinct existences? That [[hume|Humean]] 
principle reminds me that the more fundamental problem is that experiences are
_caused_ and hence cannot provide evidence for necessity (and are evidence for
possibility only in the sense that they are evidence for the actual and the
actual is always possible).

=== the limits of a priori knowledge ===
One suspects that this is at least partly the scope ofreason - that this lies
behind Kant's claims that pure reason is its own subject matter. That the
proper(?) enquiry of reason is the limits of reason.

